HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 743
By Faison
A RESOLUTION to honor the memory of Representative Gerald
Dennis McCormick II of Nashville.
WHEREAS, the members of this General Assembly were greatly saddened to learn of
the passing of our friend and former colleague Representative Gerald Dennis McCormick II; and
WHEREAS, Representative McCormick was a decorated veteran, respected public
servant, and civic leader whose life was defined by principle, integrity, and a deep commitment
to the people of Tennessee; and
WHEREAS, the former Tennessee House Majority Leader, Gerald McCormick
represented the people of Hamilton County's 26th House District with honor and distinction as a
member of the 104th, 105th, 106th, 107th, 108th, 109th, and 110th General Assemblies from 2005
until his retirement in 2018; and
WHEREAS, born on February 22, 1962, in Memphis, Representative McCormick was
raised in a family that instilled in him the values of service, scholarship, and community
engagement, shaping a life devoted to both his country and his fellow citizens; and
WHEREAS, after graduating from the University of Tennessee, Knoxville, Gerald
McCormick served honorably in the United States Army during the Gulf War as a Nuclear,
Biological, and Chemical Defense Specialist; and
WHEREAS, Representative McCormick was elected to the Tennessee House of
Representatives in 2005, representing Hamilton County's 26th District with honor and distinction
for the next fourteen years; he became one of the State's most influential Republican
lawmakers, serving as House Majority Leader from 2011 to 2014 and guiding major legislative
reforms in infrastructure, education, and business regulation; and
WHEREAS, among Leader McCormick's most notable achievements was his
instrumental support for the Tennessee Promise scholarship program, which expanded tuition-
HJR0743
011050
- 1 -

free community and technical college access to thousands of students; he also played a key
role in advancing the IMPROVE Act, one of the largest infrastructure funding efforts in State
history; and
WHEREAS, Gerald McCormick was known by colleagues for his calm demeanor,
strategic mind, and steady leadership, especially during times of rapid political change; he was
equally active outside the legislature, serving on local boards including Blood Assurance and
the Chattanooga Area Convention and Visitors Bureau; and
WHEREAS, after retiring from public office in 2018, Representative McCormick joined
The Ingram Group, under the leadership of the legendary Tom Ingram, advising on policy and
strategic initiatives that particularly related to the State of Tennessee; in 2024, he was awarded
the Distinguished Public Service Award by Kappa Alpha Order in recognition of his legacy of
servant leadership and civic duty; and
WHEREAS, Gerald McCormick is survived by his beloved wife of thirty-eight years,
Kimberly Gant McCormick; daughters, Cooper McCormick and Scottie McCormick Tudor; son-
in-law, Graham Tudor; grandchildren, Margaret "Margot" McCormick Betts and Graham "Gray"
Arthur Tudor II; his mother, Ruth McCormick; sisters, Patti Anderson and Amy Dawson; mother-
in-law, Bobbie Gant; brother and sister-in-law, Zach and Whitney Gant; brother-in-law, Scot
Woodard; lifelong friends, Matt Miller and Terry Cowdrey; loyal caregiver, Melissa Rodriguez;
and a host of other nieces, nephews, aunts, uncles, fraternity brothers, Army buddies, and
friends who were the pride of his life; and
WHEREAS, he was preceded in death by his father, Gerald Dennis McCormick I; his
sister, Melinda McCormick Woodard; his father-in-law, Harold Winston Gant; and his brother-in-
law, Harold Scott Gant; and
WHEREAS, Gerald McCormick leaves behind an indelible legacy of integrity and probity
in public life, compassion and loyalty in private life, and diligence and dedication in all his
chosen endeavors; and
- 2 - 011050

WHEREAS, it is fitting that we should remember the bountiful life of this exceptional
public servant and human being; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we honor the memory of Gerald Dennis McCormick II, reflecting fondly
upon his legacy of service, leadership, and devotion to the people of Tennessee.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we express our sympathy and offer our condolences
to the family of Representative McCormick.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
